[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-134-0792-27, Polen, Ghetto Warschau, Ghettopolizei.jpg|thumb|Ghetto Jewish Policemen|320x320px]]
The '''Kraków Ghetto Jewish Police''' were a law enforcement service in the [[Kraków Ghetto]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/33666117|title=Judenrat : the Jewish councils in Eastern Europe under Nazi occupation|last=Trunk|first=Isaiah|date=|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|year=1996|isbn=080329428X|location=Lincoln|pages=475–569|oclc=33666117}}</ref> The Kraków Ghetto Jewish Police were a local force of the ''[[Jewish Ghetto Police|Jüdischer Ordnungsdienst]],'' often abbreviated as OD.<ref name=":0" /> The OD were overseen by the [[Judenrat]] of each ghetto. The Kraków OD, unlike many other Jewish Police forces, served as willing enforcers of Nazi policies and the [[Gestapo]].<ref name=":3">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/173816773|title=The crime of my very existence : Nazism and the myth of Jewish criminality|last=Berkowitz|first=Michael|date=|publisher=University of California Press|year=2007|isbn=9780520251120|location=Berkeley|pages=59|oclc=173816773}}</ref><ref name=":1" /> Among other duties, they oversaw the liquidation of the Kraków Ghetto and helped transport Jews to [[Bełżec extermination camp]].<ref name=":2">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/476171651|title=The Yad Vashem encyclopedia of the ghettos during the Holocaust|last=|first=|date=|publisher=Yad Vashem|others=Miron, Gai., Shulhani, Shlomit., Yad ṿa-shem, rashut ha-zikaron la-Shoʼah ṿela-gevurah.|year=2009|isbn=9789653083455|location=Jerusalem|pages=126–127|oclc=476171651}}</ref>

== Leadership ==

==== Symcha Spira ====
Symcha Spira (also: Symche Spira,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=EYOu2o3h1OwC&pg=PA183&dq=Symche+Spira&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi554Ts9-raAhVohlQKHUDmAWcQ6AEINDAC#v=onepage&q=Symche%20Spira&f=false|title=Oskar Schindler: The Untold Account of His Life, Wartime Activities, and the True Story Behind the List|last=Crowe|first=David|date=2007-08-01|publisher=Basic Books|isbn=9780465008490|language=en}}</ref> Symche Spiro, or Symche Shapiro) was the Chief of the Kraków OD.<ref name=":4">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/16387568|title=The Cracow Ghetto pharmacy|last=Pankiewicz|first=Tadeusz|date=|publisher=Holocaust Library|year=1987|isbn=0896040860|edition=[2nd ed.]|location=New York|pages=6|oclc=16387568}}</ref> Unlike the Kraków Judenrat, the Kraków OD were extremely unpopular under Spira's leadership. In part because of Spira's sycophantic qualities, the Kraków OD collaborated with Nazi officials and local police to a greater degree than other ghettos.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/958799653|title=Ordinary Jews : choice and survival during the Holocaust|last=Finkel|first=Evgeny|publisher=|year=1978|isbn=9780691172576|location=Princeton, New Jersey|pages=82–83|oclc=958799653}}</ref>{{sfn|Finkel|1978|p=84}} The Civil Division of the OD in particular worked closely with the [[Gestapo]].{{sfn|Pankiewicz|1987|p=6}}

Spira infamously spoke German and Polish poorly. Before the war, he worked as a glazier, making very little money.{{sfn|Trunk|1996|p=83}} He was chosen for the position for his extreme loyalty to the Germans, as well as for his derision of his fellow Jews.<ref name=":1" /> Spira was known to wear outlandish, tailored uniforms while patrolling the ghetto.{{sfn|Berkowitz|2007|p=59}} He beat and extorted the ghetto's inhabitants, becoming very wealthy under Nazi occupation.<ref name=":1" />

==Duties==
[[File:Armband for Jewish Ghetto Police - Holocaust Museum - Odessa - Ukraine (26938755596).jpg|thumb|Armband of Jewish Ghetto Police]]
The Kraków Ghetto OD was created in July 1940, with a force of around 40 men. This number quickly grew, and in December 1940, the force had expanded to an estimated 130 men.<ref name=":1" /> Members joined in the hope of being spared punishment from Nazi officials, as well as to leverage additional favors.<ref name=":1" /> Jews who had joined in the hopes of protecting their community, like some on the Judenrat, quickly resigned when faced with rampant corruption and violence within the force.{{sfn|Trunk|1996|p=83}}

The creation of the OD was initially suggested as originating from the Judenrat, in the hope of presenting treatment of the ghetto inhabitants as a Jewish issue.{{sfn|Trunk|1996|p=475}} Spira refused to follow the direction of the Judenrat, instead deferring to [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] and [[Gestapo]] orders.{{sfn|Berkowitz|2007|p=123}} Members of the Judenrat expressed frustration at the actions of the OD, claiming they did not have the interests of fellow Jews in mind.{{sfn|Trunk|1996|p=84}}

In general, the duties of most Jewish Police forces revolved around the implementation of German orders. This involved keeping streets clear and addressing crime within the ghetto. Later, many Jewish Police forces would shift to assisting German authorities in rounding up Jews for labor, deportation, and extermination.{{sfn|Trunk|1996|p=478}} The Kraków OD often went above and beyond German orders, defying the Judenrat, and arrested Jews who smuggled in food. Extortion, bribery, and physical violence were used by Jewish Police, who recovered food and smuggled items for their own families.{{sfn|Trunk|1996|p=85-86}}

===Collaboration with Nazi Officials===
[[File:Jewish police Warsaw Ghetto.jpg|thumb|320x320px|Jewish Ghetto Police 1940/42]]
The Kraków OD were unsympathetic to resistance movements within the ghetto, and would arrest suspected members of the [[Polish Underground State|Polish Underground]] without hesitation.{{sfn|Berkowitz|2007|p=127-128}} The Jewish Police also helped to track, arrest and kill partisans alongside the [[Gestapo]].{{sfn|Berkowitz|2007|p=128}} Underground movements constantly targeted OD members, who feared being accused of collaborating with resisters.{{sfn|Trunk|1996|p=525}} The OD patrolled the ghetto carefully, searching for resistance hideouts, which they would then report to the German authorities. This participation made OD members the targets of retaliatory actions from both the Underground and German authorities.{{sfn|Trunk|1996|p=525}}

Symcha Spira took advantage of the German authorities' poor view of the Krak[[Kraków Ghetto|ó]]<nowiki/>w Judenrat, and sought to convince [[Gestapo]] agents of his superior power and influence over fellow Jews. This included carrying out orders the Judenrat would not. He and other OD men passed bribes to the [[Gestapo]], winning favors and privileges in return.{{sfn|Pankiewicz|1987|p=67}} The [[Gestapo]] promised OD members safety after the war's end, forging foreign papers for many of the men.{{sfn|Pankiewicz|1987|p=139}} Some of the OD men were also given visas for travel to other countries, which they attempted to use as conditions in the ghetto worsened.{{sfn|Pankiewicz|1987|p=140}}

==  Liquidation of Kraków Ghetto ==
[[File:Krakow Ghetto 39066.jpg|thumb|320x320px|Liquidation of Kraków Ghetto]]
The OD were also in charge of recording and preparing lists of Jews in the ghetto for deportation. They also assisted German and Polish police in rounding up Jews.{{sfn|Berkowitz|2007|p=125}} The OD would enter houses and apartments at night, taking those selected for removal under cover of darkness.{{sfn|Pankiewicz|1987|p=33}} If Jews could not present a work permit or proof of employment, they were held in the courtyard of the OD building, which had formerly been a Catholic orphanage.{{sfn|Pankiewicz|1987|p=9, 33-34}} The gathered Jews were transported the next morning by railroad car to [[Bełżec extermination camp]].{{sfn|Pankiewicz|1987|p=34}}

One of the largest deportations of residents began on May 30, 1942 and lasted until June 8th.{{sfn|Berkowitz|2007|p=126}} This was part of the larger [[Operation Reinhard in Kraków|Operation Reinhardt]] occurring across [[Occupation of Poland (1939–1945)|occupied Poland]]. Approximately 5,000 Jews without work permits or proper identification were taken via train to [[Bełżec extermination camp|Belżec]].{{sfn|Berkowitz|2007|p=126}} During this ''aktion,'' members of the OD worked alongside German and [[Blue Police|Polish Blue Police]], throwing away luggage, inspecting papers, and beating those who did not comply with orders.{{sfn|Pankiewicz|1987|p=44}}

During subsequent deportations, the OD would occasionally intervene, bribing officials when family members or friends were selected for removal. Sometimes this was successful, but other times, even Spira's interventions could not spare everyone.{{sfn|Pankiewicz|1987|p=56}} In March 1943, the ghetto was completely liquidated. Those who remained were sent to [[Kraków-Płaszów concentration camp|Plaszów]] or [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]], or were murdered on site.{{sfn|Berkowitz|2007|p=127}}

====   Fate of the Kraków OD   ====
The Kraków OD were initially exempted from deportation. After the liquidation of the ghetto, the Jewish Police assisted in cleanup and the processing of items left behind by those deported. They also assisted in moving bodies of those murdered in the ghetto. Many, including Spira, believed Nazi promises that they would be given their freedom and would be allowed to travel to America or another country after the war. Not long after the liquidation of the ghetto, the OD and all remaining Jews were deported to [[Kraków-Płaszów concentration camp|Płaszów]] and murdered.{{sfn|Pankiewicz|1987|p=149-150}}

